list.markScheme:
- We can treat the boys as a single entity and the girls as a single entity.
  There are $2!$ ways to arrange the boys and $3!$ ways to arrange the girls.
  We can arrange each entity in $2$ ways, i.e.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	\underline{B} \hspace{1em}\underline{G}\\[6pt]
  	\underline{G} \hspace{1em}\underline{B}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	2! \times 3! \times 2&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{24} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- In this case we treat the boys as a single entity.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	\underline{\textcolor{white}{B}} \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_1} \hspace{1em} \underline{\textcolor{white}{B}}  \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_2} \hspace{1em}  \underline{\textcolor{white}{B}} \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_3} \hspace{1em}  \underline{\textcolor{white}{B}} \hspace{1em}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can see above that this single entity has a choice of $4$ positions. Therefore

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	2! \times 3! \times 4&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{48} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The only way to keep all of the girls apart is place the boys between them

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	\underline{G_1} \hspace{1em} \underline{\textcolor{black}{B_1}}  \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_2} \hspace{1em}  \underline{\textcolor{black}{B_2}} \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_3}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  There is only one way to do this, hence

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	2! \times 3! \times 1&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{12} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We can use a similar diagram as part(b)

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	\underline{\textcolor{white}{B}} \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_1} \hspace{1em} \underline{\textcolor{white}{B}}  \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_2} \hspace{1em}  \underline{\textcolor{white}{B}} \hspace{1em}  \underline{G_3} \hspace{1em}  \underline{\textcolor{white}{B}} \hspace{1em}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can see $4$ positions to place the $2$ boys. Therefore there are ${}_{4}C_{2}$ ways to place the boys.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{white}{hack}\tag*{\textbf{M1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Using the formula ${}_{4}C_{2}=\tfrac{4!}{2!2!}=6$, hence

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	2! \times 3! \times 6&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{72} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$
